The best way to go nowadays (C++17 and above) is [`std::size`](https://en.cppreference.com/w/cpp/iterator/size):

    #include &lt;iterator&gt;
    ...
    int arr[5];
    static_assert(std::size(arr) == 5);

If you don&#39;t have access to C++17, it&#39;s pretty easy to roll your own too:

    template &lt;class T, size_t N&gt;
    constexpr size_t size(const T (&amp;arr)[N]) { return N; }

---

Even better, just use `std::array`, and use it&#39;s size member:

    std::array&lt;int, 5&gt; arr;
    static_assert(arr.size() == 5);

you can use `setTime()`

    let minDate = new Date();
    minDate.setTime(minDate.getTime() + 1000*60*60*24*30);

Respectively; 

1000 miliseconds = 1 seconds

60 seconds = 1 minute

60 minute = 1 hour

24 hour = 1 day

30 day = 1 month

