The OnInitializedAsync method is intended for asynchronous operations, which require re-rendering of components when the asynchronous operations are complete, and data is available. When the OnInitializedAsync method is executed, control is yielded to Blazor runtime when the asynchronous operation starts (await....), and Blazor starts rendering your view. But your Data object is not yet populated with data; it is null, and if you won&#39;t check this constraint an error is triggered. 

When the asynchronous operation completes, control is passed back to the OnInitializedAsync method which continue to execute next code if exists. Additionally, the OnInitializedAsync method calls the StateHasChanged method to re-render your component once more. And this time your Data is populated with data; it is not null, and you can traverse your Data object with foreach.

If you use the OnInitialized method instead, the rendering of the view should start after the call to your data store returns ( synchronous blocking operation). In such a case no checking is necessary at all. The checking code will never hit the part where `Data == null` . Do you realize why ?


Do you understand what this code does ?

    &lt;Component1&gt;
      @if (Data != null)
          {
            @foreach (var item in Data) {
                 &lt;Component2&gt;
            }
           }
    &lt;/Componet1&gt;

This might work, but wrongly designed. Open a new question, and let the community helps you with this...

I assume that Data is of the list or array type. What I usually do is initialize the list or array in OnInitialized and make the call in OnInitializedAsync. So no checking is necessary.

    protected override void OnInitialized()
    {
       Data = new List&lt;Type&gt;()
    }

